#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Num
{
private:
    int m_x;

public:
    Num(int val = 0) : m_x(val) {}

    // Friend functions
    friend istream& operator>>(istream& in, Num& obj);
    friend ostream& operator<<(ostream& out, const Num& obj);
};

// Overload >>
istream& operator>>(istream& in, Num& obj)
{
    cout << "Enter value: ";
    in >> obj.m_x;
    return in;
}

// Overload <<
ostream& operator<<(ostream& out, const Num& obj)
{
    out << obj.m_x;
    return out;
}

int main()
{
    Num ob;

    cin >> ob;

    cout << "Value = " << ob << endl;

    return 0;
}

=========================================
MOST ASKED OPERATOR OVERLOADING INTERVIEW Q&A
=========================================

1. What is Operator Overloading?
--------------------------------
Operator overloading allows existing C++ operators to work with user-defined types.

Example:
cout << obj;
cin >> obj;

It is an example of Compile-Time Polymorphism.

--------------------------------

2. Why overload << and >> ?
---------------------------
To make objects behave like built-in types.

Without overloading:
obj.print();

With overloading:
cout << obj;
cin >> obj;

Improves readability.

--------------------------------

3. Why are << and >> friend functions?
--------------------------------------
Because:
- They need access to private members.
- Left operand is ostream/istream.
- We cannot modify the STL ostream/istream classes.

--------------------------------

4. Why are they NOT member functions?*************************
-------------------------------------
Expression:

cout << obj;

Left operand is ostream.

Compiler converts it to:

operator<<(cout, obj);

Since ostream is an STL class, we cannot add member functions to it.

--------------------------------

5. Why return ostream& ?
------------------------
To support chaining.

Example:

cout << a << b << c;

Each operator<< returns the same ostream object.

--------------------------------

6. Why return istream& ?
------------------------
To support chaining.

Example:

cin >> a >> b >> c;

--------------------------------

7. Why does operator<< take const Object& ?
-------------------------------------------
Because it only reads the object.

Advantages:
- No copying
- Cannot modify object
- More efficient

Signature:
friend ostream& operator<<(ostream& out, const Object& obj);

--------------------------------

8. Why does operator>> take Object& ?
------------------------------------
Because input modifies the object.

Signature:
friend istream& operator>>(istream& in, Object& obj);

--------------------------------

9. What does the compiler convert this into?
--------------------------------------------

cout << obj;

becomes

operator<<(cout, obj);

Similarly,

cin >> obj;

becomes

operator>>(cin, obj);

--------------------------------

10. Why return by reference instead of value?
---------------------------------------------
- Avoids copying
- Improves performance
- Enables chaining

--------------------------------

11. Which operators MUST be member functions?
---------------------------------------------
=
[]
()
->

--------------------------------

12. Which operators are commonly overloaded as friend functions?
---------------------------------------------------------------
<<
>>

--------------------------------

13. Which OOP concept does Operator Overloading use?
----------------------------------------------------
Compile-Time Polymorphism.

--------------------------------

14. Can operator overloading change operator precedence?
--------------------------------------------------------
No.

Precedence and associativity remain unchanged.

--------------------------------

15. Can we create new operators?
--------------------------------
No.

Only existing C++ operators can be overloaded.

--------------------------------

16. What is the biggest advantage of operator overloading?
----------------------------------------------------------
Makes user-defined objects behave like built-in types.

Example:

Instead of:
obj.print();

We can write:
cout << obj;

Cleaner and more readable syntax.


